WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.840
 Quantum computers are increasingly, you know, coming along and, you know, with new breakthroughs and new papers coming every week.

00:00:06.840 --> 00:00:13.900
 It's not fair to say it's the quantum safe coin because it's not actually safe against quantum computers as it currently stands.

00:00:13.900 --> 00:00:15.640
 I was like an OG Bitcoiner.

00:00:15.640 --> 00:00:19.800
 What we're building here is something that is planetary for like hundreds of millions of users.

00:00:19.800 --> 00:00:22.280
 This is a dangerous, risky technology.

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:26.440
 I don't really separate money into store of value and medium of exchange.

00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:28.160
 I think it's like two sides of the same coin.

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:29.040
 The price is going up.

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:31.380
 Everyone says, don't change anything and ruin it.

00:00:31.380 --> 00:00:32.340
 Don't ruin it.

00:00:32.340 --> 00:00:33.600
 Don't touch it.

00:00:33.600 --> 00:00:36.920
 And when the price is going down, everyone says, let's do something.

00:00:36.920 --> 00:00:40.620
 You are a Cypherpunk advisor.

00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:41.720
 Why join Cypherpunk?

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:42.440
 Why be an advisor?

00:00:42.440 --> 00:00:49.940
 Well, they invited me to be an advisor and it seemed like a good idea at the time.

00:00:49.940 --> 00:00:53.240
 I thought Cypherpunk was going to be a DAT.

00:00:53.240 --> 00:00:57.660
 And even then, I thought a DAT was probably a good idea.

00:00:57.820 --> 00:01:07.480
 It would give various parties the ability to get price exposure to ZEK that they otherwise couldn't get because of their organizational rules or structure.

00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:09.320
 Yeah, for institutions, it's very useful.

00:01:09.320 --> 00:01:11.920
 And I trust Tyler and Cameron's intentions.

00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:16.280
 They have the right goals that I share.

00:01:16.280 --> 00:01:26.740
 And I get Cypherpunk stock options or some kind of pay, some kind of indirect pay for doing it.

00:01:27.820 --> 00:01:36.960
 So I agreed to be an advisor to Cypherpunk, which is one of only basically two professional obligations I've agreed to do at this point.

00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:41.800
 The chief product officer at Shielded Labs and an advisor to Cypherpunk.

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:49.740
 One of the big topics that's been, you know, the main, the current thing in the Zcash ecosystem has been quantum computing.

00:01:49.740 --> 00:01:57.620
 As you may be aware, quantum computers are increasingly, you know, coming along and, you know, with new breakthroughs and new papers.

00:01:57.820 --> 00:01:59.060
 Coming every week.

00:01:59.060 --> 00:02:04.640
 Some have, like, positioned Zcash as, like, the quantum safe coin.

00:02:04.640 --> 00:02:07.460
 Do you have any thoughts on that?

00:02:07.460 --> 00:02:12.240
 Like, what's your perspective of, like, Zcash's position on the quantum problem?

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:20.100
 It's not fair to say it's the quantum safe coin because it's not actually safe against quantum computers as it currently stands.

00:02:20.100 --> 00:02:27.100
 The best thing about Zcash is that there's a culture and a tradition of...

00:02:27.100 --> 00:02:30.760
 Responsible innovation.

00:02:30.760 --> 00:02:31.360
 Yeah.

00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:36.020
 Like, we don't move fast and break things, but nor do we, like, try to hold absolutely still.

00:02:36.020 --> 00:02:38.280
 Yeah, yeah, yeah, which is very important.

00:02:38.280 --> 00:02:47.400
 And Zcash has a lot of really good cryptographers and security engineers who've been thinking about this since long before it became the current thing.

00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:55.140
 And we've got some defenses against certain kinds of problems already built in.

00:02:56.380 --> 00:03:19.540
 And some of the other cryptographers, not me and not Sheldon Labs, but some of the other teams working on Zcash have developed a roadmap to further protect the users against quantum computers over the coming years in a, like, responsible, incremental fashion that doesn't disrupt or put everything at unnecessary risk, but also makes progress.

00:03:19.540 --> 00:03:20.540
 Yeah.

00:03:20.540 --> 00:03:21.640
 So that's what I like about Zcash.

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:26.220
 But it's overselling to say that Zcash is the quantum safe.

00:03:26.220 --> 00:03:31.120
 It's the quantum safe coin, because it's currently not...

00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:33.500
 No major coins currently are.

00:03:33.500 --> 00:03:33.980
 Yeah.

00:03:33.980 --> 00:03:40.640
 And they've all started, like, trying to move that direction, or at least all of them except Bitcoin have started trying to move that direction.

00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:43.100
 Yeah, we're not there yet.

00:03:43.100 --> 00:03:46.780
 I think what's promising about Zcash is there's a lot of work being done about it.

00:03:46.780 --> 00:03:48.100
 It's taken very seriously.

00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:55.480
 If a quantum solution is put forward, my guess is that it would likely be adopted just because of the culture of Zcash.

00:03:56.060 --> 00:04:02.160
 Whereas you could argue that for Bitcoin, that is much less certain due to a lot of, like, you know, divisiveness in, like, the Bitcoin community.

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:03.480
 Do you have any thoughts on that?

00:04:03.480 --> 00:04:04.740
 Yeah, I agree.

00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:06.020
 Let me put it positively.

00:04:06.020 --> 00:04:11.720
 I have this practice I'm practicing, which is don't say what's bad about a bad thing.

00:04:11.720 --> 00:04:14.920
 Instead, say what's good about a good thing.

00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:17.660
 For one thing, double negatives confuse me.

00:04:17.660 --> 00:04:21.080
 But also, it makes everyone focus better.

00:04:21.080 --> 00:04:24.860
 So what's good, I'm thinking about bad things about Bitcoin.

00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:25.300
 Yeah.

00:04:25.300 --> 00:04:26.040
 But let me express.

00:04:26.040 --> 00:04:27.160
 Let me express those good things about Zcash.

00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:38.840
 So, A, like we just said, the Zcash community is willing to evolve, like, at the right pace, carefully and responsibly, but with intention.

00:04:38.840 --> 00:04:39.240
 Yep.

00:04:39.240 --> 00:04:46.020
 And the other thing that you just mentioned is that the Zcash community is largely more, like, win-win oriented.

00:04:46.020 --> 00:04:46.460
 Yep.

00:04:46.460 --> 00:04:52.400
 Like, we may not agree on everything, but we have a lot of shared values and shared goals, and we can cooperate.

00:04:52.400 --> 00:04:55.400
 I think that's really valuable long run for...

00:04:56.020 --> 00:04:57.240
 For building.

00:04:57.240 --> 00:05:05.760
 There's a concept I saw a lot with the original, with the Bitcoin culture.

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:08.560
 I don't know if you know, but I was, like, an OG Bitcoiner.

00:05:08.560 --> 00:05:09.080
 I know, I know.

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:12.820
 I don't know if you know, but I'm the author of the first blog post ever written about Bitcoin.

00:05:12.820 --> 00:05:14.020
 I know, I know.

00:05:14.020 --> 00:05:26.000
 And there was, there developed a culture there of, it sort of, like, took the network level and cryptographic level principles that you...

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:27.820
 You want to minimize trust, right?

00:05:27.820 --> 00:05:34.180
 You want to, you don't want to be vulnerable or to take the word of another node over the network.

00:05:34.180 --> 00:05:38.600
 Instead, you want to be able to verify everything and sort of defend yourself as a node.

00:05:38.600 --> 00:05:39.260
 Yep.

00:05:39.260 --> 00:05:43.560
 And for whatever reason, people also applied that to the human level.

00:05:43.560 --> 00:05:47.760
 Like, you're not going to trust any other humans, and you're going to distrust them.

00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:55.220
 It's like the, the culture in which, sort of, bad faith is, should be the assumption.

00:05:55.220 --> 00:05:55.720
 Yes.

00:05:55.720 --> 00:05:56.920
 The assumption is bad faith.

00:05:56.920 --> 00:06:10.500
 And that was, a lot of people thought of that as, they would say, like, Bitcoin is so important that we can't be, like, namby-pamby-ing around with being nice.

00:06:10.500 --> 00:06:12.840
 It's so important that we need to be mean.

00:06:12.840 --> 00:06:17.720
 And I always thought, yeah, but, like, being nice works better.

00:06:17.720 --> 00:06:19.300
 Like, it's so important.

00:06:19.300 --> 00:06:21.160
 You want to be, you want to get stuff done.

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:21.480
 Yeah.

00:06:21.480 --> 00:06:25.700
 And human trust and cooperativeness and focusing on the world.

00:06:25.760 --> 00:06:29.040
 Win-win opportunities get stuff done in a way that distrust doesn't.

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:29.560
 Yeah.

00:06:29.560 --> 00:06:34.760
 I guess we just got onto that, because you mentioned something about the Zcash culture.

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:35.700
 I agree.

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:36.140
 I agree.

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:43.740
 I think one of the big positives, I think we were speaking of that earlier, for Zcash is really the culture, right?

00:06:43.740 --> 00:06:45.140
 This openness to innovation.

00:06:45.140 --> 00:06:52.600
 I mean, there's still, like, you know, a conservative aspect, which I think is very important for store of value.

00:06:52.600 --> 00:06:53.560
 Mm-hmm.

00:06:53.560 --> 00:06:55.140
 But the fact...

00:06:55.700 --> 00:07:02.220
 The fact that we are open to innovation and open to the ideas of others is very important for quantum,

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:08.900
 for maybe at some points potentially replacing proof-of-work for, like, these types of things.

00:07:08.900 --> 00:07:10.200
 So, yeah, I agree.

00:07:10.200 --> 00:07:11.160
 Mm-hmm.

00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:11.540
 Yeah.

00:07:11.540 --> 00:07:14.120
 Yeah, the world is never going to stop changing.

00:07:14.120 --> 00:07:14.620
 Yeah.

00:07:14.620 --> 00:07:17.000
 The needs of the people are never going to stop changing.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:17.500
 I agree.

00:07:17.500 --> 00:07:25.600
 Speaking of proof-of-work, so, like, one of the major focuses of Shielded Labs is Crosslink.

00:07:25.680 --> 00:07:36.700
 Maybe let's first cover what Crosslink is, because I think, like, the proposal has, like, changed quite a bit since, like, the original first ideas came about.

00:07:36.700 --> 00:07:44.580
 And then we can, you know, go over, like, you know, the case for it, some of the critiques, and, yeah, discuss more about it, if that's okay.

00:07:44.580 --> 00:07:55.600
 Crosslink is a proposal to change the Zcash consensus algorithm by keeping the current proof-of-work in place and adding a finality gadget.

00:07:56.080 --> 00:07:56.220
 Yep.

00:07:56.220 --> 00:08:04.860
 So I kind of think metaphorically, like, proof-of-work, which was Satoshi's big breakthrough contribution, right?

00:08:04.860 --> 00:08:13.520
 It's kind of like an engine, a self-powering engine that's always pushing forward, which is amazing and very useful.

00:08:13.520 --> 00:08:21.340
 And then the finality gadget, which used proof-of-state technology to make the finality gadget work.

00:08:21.340 --> 00:08:25.660
 Mm-hmm.

00:08:25.660 --> 00:08:26.620
 It prevents backsliding.

00:08:26.620 --> 00:08:27.720
 Okay?

00:08:27.720 --> 00:08:34.540
 Proof-of-work by itself doesn't have a notion of when a thing is permanent.

00:08:34.540 --> 00:08:35.580
 Mm-hmm.

00:08:35.580 --> 00:08:41.180
 It can always be undone by the engine pushing in a new direction.

00:08:41.180 --> 00:08:42.440
 It's probabilistic.

00:08:42.440 --> 00:08:43.500
 Right.

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:45.460
 Well, that's what people say.

00:08:45.460 --> 00:08:45.900
 Mm-hmm.

00:08:45.900 --> 00:08:51.820
 And I actually think, at, like, a mathematical level, that's a misnomer.

00:08:51.820 --> 00:08:52.640
 Mm-hmm.

00:08:55.640 --> 00:09:03.020
 I wouldn't think about security as probabilistic.

00:09:03.020 --> 00:09:13.820
 If it's worth enough to the attacker, if they have the opportunity and they have the means and the motive to take advantage of you,

00:09:13.820 --> 00:09:23.220
 it is just going to confuse you and mislead you if you think to yourself, there's a probability that they'll take advantage of me.

00:09:23.220 --> 00:09:24.560
 It's not a probability.

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:25.620
 It's whether they decide to.

00:09:25.620 --> 00:09:26.640
 It's whether they do and whether they can't.

00:09:26.640 --> 00:09:27.060
 Yes.

00:09:27.060 --> 00:09:27.540
 Yes.

00:09:27.540 --> 00:09:28.000
 Yes.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:28.520
 Correct.

00:09:28.520 --> 00:09:28.920
 Yeah.

00:09:28.920 --> 00:09:29.660
 Yeah.

00:09:29.660 --> 00:09:30.820
 That's always a risk.

00:09:30.820 --> 00:09:35.240
 I mean, and we've seen, like, these reorg attacks, like, for example, last week with Litecoin.

00:09:35.240 --> 00:09:35.540
 Yeah.

00:09:35.540 --> 00:09:36.600
 It does happen.

00:09:36.600 --> 00:09:48.560
 But, like, I guess one of, like, the main arguments then brought forward by, you know, the other camp is, well, why not just improve proof-of-work currently?

00:09:48.560 --> 00:09:50.060
 Because there's a lot to improve.

00:09:50.060 --> 00:09:55.600
 Like, I mean, until, I think, a month ago, Zcash had just, like, one big miner.

00:09:55.600 --> 00:09:58.660
 Now we have Foundry as well.

00:09:58.660 --> 00:10:04.320
 Is this maybe, like, a first path we should explore before, like, exploring Crosslink?

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:07.800
 Or are these, like, you know, not mutually exclusive?

00:10:07.800 --> 00:10:08.260
 Yeah.

00:10:08.260 --> 00:10:08.860
 They're not.

00:10:08.860 --> 00:10:11.800
 I think they're compatible and they help in different ways.

00:10:11.800 --> 00:10:25.260
 There are a bunch of other potential improvements to the proof-of-work component that the Valar team is now proposing, like, reducing the times between blocks, other kinds of performance improvements.

00:10:25.260 --> 00:10:25.580
 Yeah.

00:10:25.580 --> 00:10:30.900
 And all of those are totally compatible with the Crosslink design because it's very modular.

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:39.840
 Like, Crosslink keeps our current proposal, our design, and the prototype that we've implemented, which we're now experimenting with.

00:10:39.840 --> 00:10:46.200
 You can join the channel and play with Crosslink and help us break it.

00:10:46.200 --> 00:10:48.560
 It's very broken right now.

00:10:48.560 --> 00:10:49.940
 And that's why we do this.

00:10:49.940 --> 00:10:52.600
 Anyway, but the design is extremely modular.

00:10:52.600 --> 00:10:52.960
 Yeah.

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:55.560
 Like, any improvements, including the new...

00:10:55.560 --> 00:11:07.880
 The new mining pool foundry and the reduced block times and, like, improved peer-to-peer networking so that blocks can get communicated and transactions can get communicated faster between nodes.

00:11:07.880 --> 00:11:10.600
 All of that is perfectly compatible with Crosslink.

00:11:10.600 --> 00:11:13.560
 What Crosslink adds is primarily...

00:11:13.560 --> 00:11:17.060
 Let me try to think of the most important things.

00:11:17.060 --> 00:11:20.300
 It's got, like, quite a few different benefits that I think it offers.

00:11:20.300 --> 00:11:25.420
 But I'd say the two most important ones are irreversible finality.

00:11:25.540 --> 00:11:36.620
 So that when you can know if someone has deposited a million dollars worth of ZEC into your exchange or your DEX, like Near.

00:11:36.620 --> 00:11:37.940
 So this is what happened to Near.

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:39.080
 Well...

00:11:39.080 --> 00:11:39.780
 Yeah, with Litecoin.

00:11:39.780 --> 00:11:40.880
 They actually lost a lot of money.

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:45.600
 They lost $600,000, I think, in that event.

00:11:45.600 --> 00:11:54.540
 And it's kind of confusing whether irreversible finality would or wouldn't have fixed that in that case.

00:11:54.540 --> 00:11:55.520
 Yeah, because the transaction would have occurred.

00:11:55.680 --> 00:11:55.840
 Yeah.

00:11:55.840 --> 00:12:04.620
 But in any case, in general, if you're operating a DEX or a CEX or you're accepting large transactions over the network,

00:12:04.620 --> 00:12:08.500
 irreversible finality tells you that there's not a probability here.

00:12:08.500 --> 00:12:15.320
 It's just that once it has the stamp of finality on it, you know it cannot be undone.

00:12:15.320 --> 00:12:15.860
 Yeah.

00:12:15.860 --> 00:12:22.860
 That's a much simpler and safer guarantee to reason about as an operator.

00:12:22.860 --> 00:12:23.640
 Correct.

00:12:23.640 --> 00:12:24.140
 Correct.

00:12:24.140 --> 00:12:25.100
 Yes, that makes sense.

00:12:25.100 --> 00:12:25.500
 Oh, and the other...

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:36.760
 The second biggest advantage of Crosslink is that it magnifies the security budget, in a sense.

00:12:36.760 --> 00:12:45.380
 And we have a more precise technical definition of this number, but people call it informally, they call it the security budget.

00:12:45.380 --> 00:12:52.400
 And that's a thing which in Bitcoin and in Zcash, it's tied to the issuance.

00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:52.840
 Yep.

00:12:52.840 --> 00:12:53.200
 Right?

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:55.200
 And the issuance ticks down over time.

00:12:55.480 --> 00:12:55.860
 Of course, yeah.

00:12:55.860 --> 00:13:02.320
 And like with Quantum, this is a thing where I think it will be a problem for Bitcoin,

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:07.040
 and I don't know if they have the right culture to be willing to make changes to address the problem.

00:13:07.040 --> 00:13:07.320
 Yep.

00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:17.960
 And in Zcash, it's got the same problem because Bitcoin and Zcash are the two coins that want to maintain a hard, fixed cap on the supply.

00:13:17.960 --> 00:13:18.560
 Yep.

00:13:18.560 --> 00:13:24.660
 There's only ever 21 million Bitcoins, only ever 21 million Zcash, and almost everyone agrees to that.

00:13:24.660 --> 00:13:25.340
 That's the golden rule.

00:13:25.340 --> 00:13:36.100
 Very few people want to change that, but there's substantial, maybe 10% or 20% of all the Zcashers would be happy to change the supply in order to gain the sustainability.

00:13:36.100 --> 00:13:36.780
 Yes.

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:54.420
 So at Shielded Labs, we have two projects, and one of them is Crosslink, which we think can provide the sustainability and thus sort of harden the assurance that the supply will remain limited.

00:13:54.420 --> 00:13:55.020
 Yep.

00:13:55.200 --> 00:14:04.700
 Whereas with Ethereum, they long since accepted a variable supply in return for various other trade-offs.

00:14:04.700 --> 00:14:08.580
 And in Bitcoin, I don't know what their plan is.

00:14:08.580 --> 00:14:13.880
 They're committed to the fixed supply, but they don't know how they're going to provide the sustainability.

00:14:13.880 --> 00:14:14.640
 Yeah, yeah.

00:14:14.640 --> 00:14:24.560
 So two of Shielded Labs' projects, Network Sustainability Mechanism and also Crosslink, both contribute to sustainability while hardening the 21 million supply cap.

00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:24.940
 Yeah.

00:14:25.060 --> 00:14:25.420
 That makes sense.

00:14:25.420 --> 00:14:49.200
 Because like the problem with Bitcoin is, and it's such a logical problem, I fail to understand how people cannot see that it's a problem, is if you're allocating like a security budget every year to mining, which the inflation on Bitcoin is effectively, and you're halving that security budget every four years, you need the price to catch up and compensate, which at some point it might not.

00:14:49.200 --> 00:14:54.920
 And when it does not, when it doesn't, you're going to be in big trouble because your security budget.

00:14:54.920 --> 00:14:55.700
 Effectively halves.

00:14:55.700 --> 00:15:02.580
 And so at some points, it's practically guaranteed we'll need like an alternative system.

00:15:02.580 --> 00:15:03.140
 Seems like it.

00:15:03.140 --> 00:15:04.600
 And there's transaction fees.

00:15:04.600 --> 00:15:05.200
 Yes.

00:15:05.200 --> 00:15:06.280
 But those are not enough.

00:15:06.280 --> 00:15:06.880
 But that's also.

00:15:06.880 --> 00:15:08.140
 Like a Bitcoin, it's very little.

00:15:08.140 --> 00:15:08.540
 Questionable.

00:15:08.540 --> 00:15:08.880
 Yeah.

00:15:08.880 --> 00:15:09.300
 Yes.

00:15:09.300 --> 00:15:23.840
 A thing about Crosslink, one of the two biggest features or benefits of Crosslink is that if you take your security budget, your issuance, which can come from unissued coins, right?

00:15:23.840 --> 00:15:24.860
 Because we're still below.

00:15:24.860 --> 00:15:25.640
 Twenty one million.

00:15:25.640 --> 00:15:34.300
 So we can issue more and it can come from past fees because with shielded labs is network sustainability mechanism.

00:15:34.300 --> 00:15:44.580
 Sixty percent of the fees get burned, so 40% of the fees goes to the current minor of the next block and 60% of the fee gets burned.

00:15:44.580 --> 00:15:54.380
 And in the network sustainability mechanism, everything that's ever been burned can be reincarnated months and years later to add to the sustainability.

00:15:54.380 --> 00:15:54.720
 But.

00:15:54.720 --> 00:15:59.920
 Maybe a dumb question, but wouldn't that then reduce the security budget for mining?

00:15:59.920 --> 00:16:03.020
 I mean, I'm guessing that you are then rewarding miners less.

00:16:03.020 --> 00:16:07.700
 The fee burning or the issuance part?

00:16:07.700 --> 00:16:12.960
 Well, for the fee burning, like the fees you're burning previously, I'm assuming they went to miners.

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:13.160
 Right.

00:16:13.160 --> 00:16:15.780
 Currently, 100% of the fees go to miners.

00:16:15.780 --> 00:16:15.960
 Yep.

00:16:15.960 --> 00:16:24.580
 And in the NSM proposal, which is going up for some kind of governance vote shortly, but it's already been voted on.

00:16:24.580 --> 00:16:28.080
 It's been voted on once and everyone approved this part of it the last time around.

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:32.800
 But anyway, in that proposal, 60% of each fee gets burned.

00:16:32.800 --> 00:16:35.860
 That only leaves 40% of the fee for the current miner.

00:16:35.860 --> 00:16:44.260
 However, that's enough to incentivize them to include that transaction because it's very cheap for them to add a transaction in.

00:16:44.260 --> 00:16:46.300
 Yeah. So your bet is that they will do it anyway.

00:16:46.300 --> 00:16:54.440
 And they're still motivated to include transactions at the current levels.

00:16:54.440 --> 00:16:59.340
 Like with Bitcoin, the fees are very little in real money terms.

00:16:59.340 --> 00:16:59.740
 Oh, yeah.

00:16:59.740 --> 00:17:01.300
 Like it's compared to inflation.

00:17:01.300 --> 00:17:01.920
 Yeah.

00:17:01.920 --> 00:17:09.880
 But this is, we're very like long term and sustainability and like economic balance oriented at Shielded Labs.

00:17:09.880 --> 00:17:16.500
 So almost all of our projects are focused on like if we got this into place, got everyone to agree to it.

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:16.780
 Yep.

00:17:16.780 --> 00:17:19.100
 And then the world radically changed.

00:17:19.100 --> 00:17:21.880
 How would the network do in that situation?

00:17:21.880 --> 00:17:22.340
 Yes.

00:17:22.340 --> 00:17:22.740
 Yes.

00:17:22.740 --> 00:17:23.140
 Yeah.

00:17:23.140 --> 00:17:23.540
 Yeah.

00:17:23.540 --> 00:17:24.300
 And I think it is.

00:17:24.300 --> 00:17:33.460
 I think it is very important to plan for like the future where like what we're building here is something that is planetary for like hundreds of millions of users.

00:17:33.460 --> 00:17:34.200
 That's the plan.

00:17:34.200 --> 00:17:34.760
 That's the goal.

00:17:34.760 --> 00:17:43.380
 We don't want to, you know, like it's nice to have our little community of like, you know, a few hundreds, maybe a few thousands of people who are very committed to Zcash.

00:17:43.380 --> 00:17:48.020
 But the end goal is millions of users, millions of transactions every day.

00:17:48.020 --> 00:17:49.380
 And yeah.

00:17:49.380 --> 00:17:53.060
 Which increase the fees, increase the load.

00:17:53.060 --> 00:17:53.480
 Yes.

00:17:53.480 --> 00:17:54.000
 Yes.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:18:00.580
 And increase all the sort of like stress on makers of software and services and everything.

00:18:00.580 --> 00:18:01.540
 Correct.

00:18:01.540 --> 00:18:07.520
 And those hundreds of millions or however many users, they make it much harder to change things.

00:18:07.520 --> 00:18:08.080
 Yes.

00:18:08.080 --> 00:18:08.600
 Yes.

00:18:08.600 --> 00:18:09.100
 Yes.

00:18:09.100 --> 00:18:09.920
 Yes.

