 I'm hoping to get these things in now because I think they're like long term.

00:18:13.680 --> 00:18:15.260
 Because later on it will be much harder.

00:18:15.260 --> 00:18:15.680
 Yeah.

00:18:15.680 --> 00:18:16.100
 Probably.

00:18:16.100 --> 00:18:16.700
 Hopefully.

00:18:16.700 --> 00:18:17.360
 Yeah.

00:18:17.360 --> 00:18:17.980
 Hopefully.

00:18:17.980 --> 00:18:18.380
 Hopefully.

00:18:18.380 --> 00:18:18.720
 Indeed.

00:18:18.720 --> 00:18:19.060
 Indeed.

00:18:19.060 --> 00:18:19.140
 Indeed.

00:18:19.140 --> 00:18:19.420
 Indeed.

00:18:19.420 --> 00:18:22.560
 I guess to close on the crosslink chapter.

00:18:22.560 --> 00:18:23.760
 Like what are the other?

00:18:23.860 --> 00:18:24.340
 The critiques.

00:18:24.340 --> 00:18:26.280
 I think Mert has given his critique.

00:18:26.280 --> 00:18:33.720
 I myself do resonate with it as well is that it might make the protocol too complex or too complicated.

00:18:33.720 --> 00:18:34.240
 Yeah.

00:18:34.240 --> 00:18:36.440
 Because you're introducing a lot of like new variables.

00:18:36.440 --> 00:18:39.000
 Like proof of work is great because it's pretty simple.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:39.500
 Yeah.

00:18:39.500 --> 00:18:41.760
 Like it's really just very simple.

00:18:41.760 --> 00:18:42.240
 Turns out.

00:18:42.240 --> 00:18:44.700
 Like the miners guess like an ounce.

00:18:44.700 --> 00:18:46.780
 Turns out to be pretty complicated in practice.

00:18:46.780 --> 00:18:47.560
 But yes.

00:18:47.560 --> 00:18:49.960
 Even simple things turn out to be really complicated.

00:18:49.960 --> 00:18:52.960
 So I really resonate too with that factor.

00:18:53.860 --> 00:18:59.020
 That critique that like complexity is definitely the enemy especially for store value.

00:18:59.020 --> 00:18:59.620
 Yeah.

00:18:59.620 --> 00:19:00.120
 Yeah.

00:19:00.120 --> 00:19:00.640
 Right.

00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:10.320
 Because we want confidence, reliability, safety, even in face of attack, attempted exploitation, all kinds of attacks from different parties.

00:19:10.320 --> 00:19:12.800
 So I totally agree with that.

00:19:12.800 --> 00:19:17.300
 There's an aspect of our current crosslink design, which is kind of targeted that way.

00:19:17.300 --> 00:19:19.620
 I'm not saying they're wrong to critique it.

00:19:19.620 --> 00:19:23.700
 Like it's definitely two things is way more complicated than one, like more than twice.

00:19:23.700 --> 00:19:24.480
 It's complicated.

00:19:24.480 --> 00:19:25.020
 Right.

00:19:25.020 --> 00:19:33.140
 Like two things is a lot, but there's an aspect of it, which I'm pretty satisfied with.

00:19:33.140 --> 00:19:43.320
 And we solicited some sort of independent analysis from economics, mechanism design to try to double check if we're getting this right.

00:19:43.320 --> 00:19:47.580
 But there are different components and each component only has one job.

00:19:47.580 --> 00:19:48.320
 Yeah.

00:19:48.320 --> 00:19:53.540
 And so in a way that simplifies things like in the current in Bitcoin.

00:19:53.540 --> 00:20:06.920
 And in Zcash currently, the proof of work miners, people are counting on them both to keep making progress and including transactions and not to backslide too much.

00:20:06.920 --> 00:20:07.420
 Yeah.

00:20:07.420 --> 00:20:10.360
 So they kind of have two sort of competing goals.

00:20:10.360 --> 00:20:10.860
 Yes.

00:20:10.860 --> 00:20:23.380
 And then they normally do this well, but of course it gets more complicated when due to load due to like bugs that are coming out from the cyber.

00:20:23.380 --> 00:20:30.300
 Security, AI, wave, things like that, the complications compound.

00:20:30.300 --> 00:20:30.800
 Yeah.

00:20:30.800 --> 00:20:36.840
 And a thing that I really like about the current crosslink design is now there's two components, but each one only has one job.

00:20:36.840 --> 00:20:37.340
 Yeah.

00:20:37.340 --> 00:20:50.180
 The proof of work miners can't backslide or undo anybody's transaction, even if they tried, and they don't need to worry about that because the finalizers, it's called validators in other blockchains.

00:20:50.180 --> 00:20:50.660
 It's called validators in other blockchains.

00:20:50.660 --> 00:20:51.300
 It's called validators in other blockchains.

00:20:51.300 --> 00:20:51.760
 It's called validators in other blockchains.

00:20:51.760 --> 00:20:52.260
 It's called validators in other blockchains.

00:20:52.260 --> 00:20:52.760
 It's called validators in other blockchains.

00:20:52.760 --> 00:20:53.260
 It's called validators in other blockchains.

00:20:53.260 --> 00:20:53.260
 It's called validators in other blockchains.

00:20:53.260 --> 00:20:53.260
 It's called validators in other blockchains.

00:20:53.260 --> 00:20:53.260
 It's called validators in other blockchains.

00:20:53.260 --> 00:20:53.800
 It's called validators in other blockchains.

00:20:53.800 --> 00:20:56.600
 But in crosslink, they don't validate anything.

00:20:56.600 --> 00:21:03.800
 All they do is put the stamp of approval that this thing cannot be undone, the irreversible stamp, okay?

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:10.920
 And so the finalizers, they just have one job, just put the irreversible stamp on things and never undo it.

00:21:10.920 --> 00:21:13.180
 They, as a component, they can be simpler.

00:21:13.180 --> 00:21:17.920
 They're not responsible for including transactions, dealing with all the other like issues.

00:21:17.920 --> 00:21:20.300
 Yeah, they do one thing, they do it well, you know.

00:21:20.300 --> 00:21:20.840
 Yeah.

00:21:20.840 --> 00:21:23.140
 So I agree, complexity is the hard part.

00:21:23.140 --> 00:21:27.020
 And we're always fighting against complexity at all levels.

00:21:27.020 --> 00:21:29.100
 Let's move forward to a new topic.

00:21:29.100 --> 00:21:36.340
 Like you were speaking about, you know, the other proposals of Shielded Labs being NSM and dynamic fees.

00:21:36.340 --> 00:21:38.800
 Any update on those?

00:21:38.800 --> 00:21:46.840
 My understanding is that both were put forward in the last NU7, I think, voting proposal.

00:21:46.840 --> 00:21:48.560
 I think the voting was confused.

00:21:48.560 --> 00:21:49.140
 Okay.

00:21:49.140 --> 00:21:53.020
 Because the actual ballot said,

00:21:53.020 --> 00:21:57.820
 for each of, there was many questions, like 12 or something, different questions, or 10.

00:21:57.820 --> 00:22:06.640
 And the ballot said things like, do you generally like the idea of fees being based on market conditions or adapting or whatever?

00:22:06.640 --> 00:22:07.400
 Yeah.

00:22:07.400 --> 00:22:21.600
 But then, sort of the accompanying extra information said, this question is about this specific protocol in a draft Zcash improvement proposal in like GitHub.

00:22:21.600 --> 00:22:22.900
 So now it's ambiguous.

00:22:22.900 --> 00:22:28.780
 Are you voting for and against the general idea or are you voting for or against this specific preliminary protocol?

00:22:28.780 --> 00:22:29.280
 Yeah.

00:22:29.280 --> 00:22:48.280
 Anyway, a bunch of the, like, interest groups, there's a voting body that's all the core devs, and there's like the Zcash Brazil community, and then there's like the Zcash Foundation's longstanding advisory panel that's been doing this for like eight years or whatever.

00:22:48.280 --> 00:22:48.780
 Yeah.

00:22:48.780 --> 00:22:51.280
 I think they all voted in favor of the dynamic fees.

00:22:51.280 --> 00:22:55.120
 They all voted in favor of the dynamic fees item.

00:22:55.120 --> 00:22:59.160
 And then 80% of the coin holders voted against the dynamic fees item.

00:22:59.160 --> 00:23:01.660
 Okay.

00:23:01.660 --> 00:23:09.900
 And one guy, Dave from the Valar group, posted his rationale on Twitter as to how he, why he voted how he voted.

00:23:09.900 --> 00:23:18.320
 He voted against dynamic fees, saying the reason was he disagreed with some specific detail of the draft protocol.

00:23:18.320 --> 00:23:21.160
 Anyway, I don't know.

00:23:21.160 --> 00:23:22.580
 I don't know if there's going to be another vote.

00:23:22.580 --> 00:23:23.120
 Yeah.

00:23:23.120 --> 00:23:26.160
 Some, like, other people are organizing that stuff.

00:23:26.160 --> 00:23:31.540
 I think there's also, like, still a lot of room for, like, the, you know, voting to be improved.

00:23:31.540 --> 00:23:46.740
 Whether it being available in, you know, in Soddle and Zyngo and other Zcash wallets, but also, obviously, like, the questions should be, like, very, very clear and simple so, you know, everyone knows what they're actually voting on and what they're not voting on.

00:23:46.740 --> 00:23:47.540
 Right.

00:23:47.540 --> 00:23:50.080
 Or at least they're all voting on the same question as each other for starters.

00:23:50.080 --> 00:23:51.040
 Yeah.

00:23:51.040 --> 00:23:59.660
 Because, yeah, in this case, for example, it's very hard to actually learn actionable information from it because we actually don't know what the reasoning was behind it.

00:23:59.660 --> 00:24:00.160
 Yeah.

00:24:00.160 --> 00:24:03.160
 Like, if actually people understood the right, like, the question.

00:24:03.160 --> 00:24:04.000
 Yeah.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:05.960
 Yeah, and which question, as you said, they voted on.

00:24:05.960 --> 00:24:07.660
 Yeah, it'd be interesting if there was some process.

00:24:07.660 --> 00:24:08.160
 I don't know.

00:24:08.160 --> 00:24:09.160
 I'm speculating here.

00:24:09.160 --> 00:24:20.920
 It's not really my department, but it'd be cool if there was something that were more deliberative or people had to post their rationales along with their votes or something.

00:24:20.920 --> 00:24:26.580
 Then we'd learn a lot more because just a yay/nay vote on a specific question could be interpreted a lot of different ways.

00:24:26.580 --> 00:24:43.420
 Yeah, or maybe, as I think you had mentioned in the earlier discussion, have sub-questions where it's yes to this specific outcome, no to this specific, like, yes to this other specific outcome, or, like, just no, kill it and let's just not do this.

00:24:43.420 --> 00:24:49.840
 For example, like, you know, for issuance curves, like, this curve, this curve, or just no curve at all, like, we don't change anything.

00:24:49.840 --> 00:24:50.800
 Yeah.

00:24:50.800 --> 00:24:53.680
 I think that, you know, that would be way more actionable and, yeah, just way more useful.

00:24:53.680 --> 00:24:54.140
 Makes sense.

00:24:54.140 --> 00:25:06.420
 And this is an example of, like, responding to the previous vote by asking a more specific or clarifying question or seeing if some people are going to shift and converge between then and now or something.

00:25:06.420 --> 00:25:11.960
 So it's more, I don't know, an interactive process than a one-shot vote.

00:25:11.960 --> 00:25:12.460
 Yeah.

00:25:12.460 --> 00:25:20.680
 I think you had had some conversations with Daira Emma about coin-weighted voting, and I think she was generally against it.

00:25:20.680 --> 00:25:22.800
 You were in favor?

00:25:22.800 --> 00:25:24.600
 I don't remember this conversation last year.

00:25:24.600 --> 00:25:25.140
 Oh, too bad.

00:25:25.140 --> 00:25:26.340
 Was this on the forum?

00:25:26.340 --> 00:25:27.520
 I'm guessing, yeah.

00:25:27.520 --> 00:25:30.980
 Like, what's your position right now on coin-weighted voting?

00:25:30.980 --> 00:25:33.600
 Like, what's, you know, are you in favor of it?

00:25:33.600 --> 00:25:44.560
 Well, historically, there was a time when most people who were active in the Zcash community were against it for valid reasons.

00:25:44.560 --> 00:25:50.560
 One of them was Vitalik Buterin, who was always a Zcacher in addition to being an Ethereum person.

00:25:50.560 --> 00:25:57.560
 And others were like Peter Van Valkenburg, who's now, at the time, he was on the Zcash Foundation Board of Directors.

00:25:57.560 --> 00:26:02.220
 He subsequently stepped down from that in order to become the executive director of Coin Center.

00:26:02.220 --> 00:26:03.220
 Yeah, that makes sense, yeah.

00:26:03.220 --> 00:26:11.220
 But Vitalik and Peter and others expressed concerns about, like, the risks or downsides of coin-weighted voting.

00:26:11.220 --> 00:26:20.440
 And my position at the time was, well, yeah, but those are risks if the coin holders have, like, all of the...

00:26:20.440 --> 00:26:21.440
 Yeah.

00:26:21.440 --> 00:26:22.440
 ...power.

00:26:22.440 --> 00:26:23.440
 Yeah.

00:26:23.440 --> 00:26:24.440
 All of the decision.

00:26:24.440 --> 00:26:25.440
 And currently, they have, like, zero power or zero voice at all.

00:26:25.440 --> 00:26:26.440
 Yeah.

00:26:26.440 --> 00:26:31.440
 Like, nobody even knows what they think, much less will give them any credence.

00:26:31.440 --> 00:26:32.440
 Yes, yeah.

00:26:32.440 --> 00:26:37.440
 And my position at the time was, so, I think they should have somewhere between, like, one-thirds and two-thirds of the power.

00:26:37.440 --> 00:26:38.440
 Yeah.

00:26:38.440 --> 00:26:44.440
 And then it's probably not going to run into those, like, total risks on that side and probably not the total risks on this side.

00:26:44.440 --> 00:26:45.440
 Yeah.

00:26:45.440 --> 00:26:49.320
 This is typical of me to figure, like, the extremes are more risky...

00:26:49.320 --> 00:26:50.320
 Yeah.

00:26:50.320 --> 00:26:52.320
 ...and the middle ground is probably safer sometimes.

00:26:52.320 --> 00:26:53.320
 Yeah.

00:26:53.320 --> 00:26:54.320
 Okay.

00:26:54.320 --> 00:26:55.320
 Well, I still think that.

00:26:55.320 --> 00:26:59.320
 I still think coin holders should have between one-thirds and two-thirds of the political power.

00:26:59.320 --> 00:27:00.320
 Yeah.

00:27:00.320 --> 00:27:03.320
 It's totally unclear to me how much they currently have.

00:27:03.320 --> 00:27:08.320
 I think it's technically a third, but, like, it's all in just, like, culture, right?

00:27:08.320 --> 00:27:09.320
 Like, I mean...

00:27:09.320 --> 00:27:10.320
 Right.

00:27:10.320 --> 00:27:11.320
 There's no strict rule.

00:27:11.320 --> 00:27:16.320
 Like, there's a funny thing about political power is if you convince someone you have it and there's no point...

00:27:16.320 --> 00:27:17.320
 Yes.

00:27:17.320 --> 00:27:19.320
 ...in resisting you, then you have it.

00:27:19.320 --> 00:27:20.200
 Yeah.

00:27:20.200 --> 00:27:21.200
 Yeah.

00:27:21.200 --> 00:27:25.200
 Now, the one technical thing that I can tell without trying to infer a culture...

00:27:25.200 --> 00:27:26.200
 Yeah.

00:27:26.200 --> 00:27:30.200
 ...is that coin holders control, I think it's 60% of the funding.

00:27:30.200 --> 00:27:31.200
 Yeah.

00:27:31.200 --> 00:27:36.200
 Because 60% of the funding goes to retroactive grants determined solely by the coin holder votes.

00:27:36.200 --> 00:27:37.200
 Yeah.

00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:43.200
 40% of the funding goes to other kinds of grants controlled solely by the Zcash Community Grants Committee.

00:27:43.200 --> 00:27:44.200
 Yeah.

00:27:44.200 --> 00:27:49.200
 I think of the 20% that is going to the DEF Fund, it's 12% that's going to one and 8% are going to the other.

00:27:49.200 --> 00:27:50.080
 Exactly.

00:27:50.080 --> 00:27:51.080
 Yeah, that's correct.

00:27:51.080 --> 00:27:52.080
 Same numbers.

00:27:52.080 --> 00:27:53.080
 Yeah, same numbers.

00:27:53.080 --> 00:27:56.080
 So that fits nicely within my one-third to two-third range.

00:27:56.080 --> 00:27:57.080
 Yeah.

