 change over time, but you can develop and test and get people to start using the thing.

00:40:37.480 --> 00:40:38.480
 Yeah.

00:40:38.480 --> 00:40:42.720
 The more you do that, then the more knowledge and understanding people have, the more mature

00:40:42.720 --> 00:40:49.660
 the thing is, and the more you and others can judge what are the actual trade-offs of

00:40:49.660 --> 00:40:50.660
 this.

00:40:50.660 --> 00:40:51.660
 Yeah.

00:40:51.660 --> 00:40:54.140
 There might or might not be a future.

00:40:54.140 --> 00:40:55.680
 So that's what we're currently doing with Crosslink.

00:40:55.680 --> 00:40:58.660
 We've got this prototype that we've implemented.

00:40:58.660 --> 00:41:04.600
 It's very buggy, which is very good opportunity to find bugs and learn how things can go wrong.

00:41:04.600 --> 00:41:05.600
 Yeah.

00:41:05.600 --> 00:41:12.600
 And we've got a very active community of developers who are building their own block

00:41:12.600 --> 00:41:15.640
 servers and patches and stuff.

00:41:15.640 --> 00:41:18.540
 And just users who want to run it and see how it runs.

00:41:18.540 --> 00:41:23.360
 So there's a really good feedback loop, both we're learning from them and they're learning

00:41:23.360 --> 00:41:25.940
 from Shield Labs, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

00:41:25.940 --> 00:41:28.140
 I think that's a really good process.

00:41:28.140 --> 00:41:32.800
 In the past, we had the opposite process in Zcash, which was like the whole community

00:41:32.800 --> 00:41:35.120
 will decide if this is a good idea.

00:41:35.120 --> 00:41:39.540
 Having made that decision, then some developers will go off for the next few years and implement

00:41:39.540 --> 00:41:40.540
 the thing.

00:41:40.540 --> 00:41:41.540
 Yeah.

00:41:41.540 --> 00:41:42.920
 And that's the wrong way around.

00:41:42.920 --> 00:41:45.380
 And a good example is ZSAs.

00:41:45.380 --> 00:41:50.940
 Like three years ago, the entire Zcash community, except for me, said, "That's a great idea.

00:41:50.940 --> 00:41:54.780
 We should definitely prioritize that as one of the most important priorities."

00:41:54.780 --> 00:41:58.900
 So now a bunch of developers have spent three years and millions of dollars implementing

00:41:58.900 --> 00:42:06.600
 that thing, at which point some faction or one-thirds or two-thirds or whatever of the

00:42:06.600 --> 00:42:09.420
 Zcash community said, "Actually, we don't want that thing."

00:42:09.420 --> 00:42:10.420
 Yeah.

00:42:10.420 --> 00:42:11.420
 Yeah.

00:42:11.420 --> 00:42:13.460
 It's too late and too early.

00:42:13.460 --> 00:42:17.420
 We don't even know how ZSAs would work in practice, because no one's ever implemented

00:42:17.420 --> 00:42:23.140
 a wallet and ever, to my knowledge, maybe someone has, but I've never seen a wallet

00:42:23.140 --> 00:42:26.040
 that could actually use a ZSA for anything.

00:42:26.040 --> 00:42:29.980
 But it's also too late, because we've already spent millions of dollars and many years of

00:42:29.980 --> 00:42:32.140
 skilled teams' time to implement it.

00:42:32.140 --> 00:42:35.720
 Anyway, so we're trying to do things in the other order with Crosslink, where you implement

00:42:35.720 --> 00:42:40.740
 it first, you can see how it works, what it does and doesn't do, what the trade-offs are,

00:42:40.740 --> 00:42:45.820
 and then either the Zcash community changes their -- well, the ones who currently oppose

00:42:45.820 --> 00:42:49.580
 it change their minds and say, "Actually, that doesn't look so bad," and then we could

00:42:49.580 --> 00:42:56.040
 collectively -- the whole Zcash ecosystem and community could upgrade the central main

00:42:56.040 --> 00:43:03.180
 net to add Crosslink, especially because we designed it to be very modular and sort of

00:43:03.180 --> 00:43:05.360
 deployable.

00:43:05.360 --> 00:43:09.100
 Or if they're still not into it, then we have this interesting situation where you've got

00:43:09.100 --> 00:43:10.620
 this like...

00:43:10.620 --> 00:43:11.880
 It's kind of like a sidechain.

00:43:11.880 --> 00:43:19.180
 It doesn't have the economic linkage to real Zec, but it has the community and the functionality.

00:43:19.180 --> 00:43:20.180
 I don't know.

00:43:20.180 --> 00:43:26.160
 There may be some way to keep it growing on the side.

00:43:26.160 --> 00:43:32.520
 Anyway, I wouldn't be surprised if this same sort of process turns out to be good for Tachyon.

00:43:32.520 --> 00:43:33.520
 Yeah.

00:43:33.520 --> 00:43:34.520
 Yeah.

00:43:34.520 --> 00:43:40.500
 Speaking of the sidechain, I think one of the proposals someone has floated around was

00:43:40.500 --> 00:43:46.960
 the idea of having some sort of cannery network, as they call it, sort of like Polkadot or Kusama

00:43:46.960 --> 00:43:53.320
 I think it's called, where we can kind of like go crazy and like -- I mean, go crazy

00:43:53.320 --> 00:43:54.320
 with a certain bounce, right?

00:43:54.320 --> 00:43:55.320
 Right.

00:43:55.320 --> 00:43:59.540
 Like move fast and break things in a safe space.

00:43:59.540 --> 00:44:04.660
 So that we can be maybe more conservative on the main chain and then only really implement

00:44:04.660 --> 00:44:06.860
 like the really very, very solid stuff.

00:44:06.860 --> 00:44:07.860
 Right.

00:44:07.860 --> 00:44:08.860
 Yeah.

00:44:08.860 --> 00:44:09.860
 That's a very interesting proposal in my opinion.

00:44:09.860 --> 00:44:10.380
 Yeah.

00:44:10.380 --> 00:44:11.820
 And I think that's one of the best turnstiles.

00:44:11.820 --> 00:44:18.620
 One of my other favorite technologies, also underappreciated for many years, but now people

00:44:18.620 --> 00:44:22.140
 appreciate them because they've saved our bacon multiple times.

00:44:22.140 --> 00:44:29.640
 And it's one of those Zcash innovations that I hope other cryptocurrencies and technologies

00:44:29.640 --> 00:44:35.900
 will sort of start -- I think they'll eventually realize once they have the hard experience

00:44:35.900 --> 00:44:39.260
 themselves of, "Oh, if only we had had a turnstile here, wouldn't that be great?"

00:44:39.260 --> 00:44:40.260
 Yes.

00:44:40.260 --> 00:44:46.280
 And turnstiles like these side chains and this canary network, it's like you could imagine

00:44:46.280 --> 00:44:49.720
 hypothetically -- I don't know how this would work, but you can imagine we're going to make

00:44:49.720 --> 00:44:57.120
 a pool that is going to be interoperable with the Zcash main chain, but this is a dangerous,

00:44:57.120 --> 00:44:58.720
 risky technology.

00:44:58.720 --> 00:45:01.700
 So it has a turnstile and there's like a limit.

00:45:01.700 --> 00:45:05.500
 You can't have more than 10,000 Zcash in this pool at a time.

00:45:05.500 --> 00:45:06.500
 Yeah.

00:45:06.500 --> 00:45:07.500
 Interesting.

00:45:07.500 --> 00:45:10.140
 Or you can't move more than 100 Zcash a day into this pool.

00:45:10.140 --> 00:45:11.900
 Or something like that.

00:45:11.900 --> 00:45:17.140
 Then if this one has a catastrophic failure, it's not going to hurt everyone else who chose

00:45:17.140 --> 00:45:18.140
 to not risk it.

00:45:18.140 --> 00:45:19.140
 Yeah, the exposure is limited.

00:45:19.140 --> 00:45:20.140
 Yeah.

00:45:20.140 --> 00:45:21.140
 It's interesting.

00:45:21.140 --> 00:45:22.140
 I don't know.

00:45:22.140 --> 00:45:23.140
 There's a lot of possibilities for the future.

00:45:23.140 --> 00:45:24.140
 Yeah.

00:45:24.140 --> 00:45:26.300
 It's definitely something that should be considered.

00:45:26.300 --> 00:45:27.300
 For sure.

00:45:27.300 --> 00:45:28.300
 I agree.

00:45:28.300 --> 00:45:29.300
 Yeah.

00:45:29.300 --> 00:45:32.200
 Last question is for the future of Zcash.

00:45:32.200 --> 00:45:33.200
 What's your vision?

00:45:33.200 --> 00:45:40.020
 I know you wrote this blog post, was it a year or two ago, about like honoring the holder.

00:45:40.020 --> 00:45:46.480
 What's your vision of Zcash for the next decade or so?

00:45:46.480 --> 00:45:48.260
 How do you envision Zcash?

00:45:48.260 --> 00:45:53.860
 I know a lot of people have now started really thinking of Zcash as a store of value.

00:45:53.860 --> 00:45:57.860
 But I mean, there's like cash in the name Zcash.

00:45:57.860 --> 00:46:06.780
 So have you a particular opinion about that, about the use cases, about your vision of

00:46:06.780 --> 00:46:07.780
 Zcash?

00:46:07.780 --> 00:46:08.780
 Has that changed?

00:46:08.780 --> 00:46:09.900
 I think of...

00:46:09.900 --> 00:46:15.720
 I don't really separate money into store of value and medium of exchange.

00:46:15.720 --> 00:46:19.600
 I think it's like two sides of the same coin or whatever, the chicken and the egg.

00:46:19.600 --> 00:46:23.340
 It's really the same thing.

00:46:23.340 --> 00:46:39.780
 My vision is Zcash continues to grow in distribution, users, and security and sustainability.

